{
  "_dft": {
    "_doc": "MISR zoo — five Multiple Input Signature Registers, each illustrating a different state of the SIGNATURE COMPACTORS panel:\n\n  • MISR_match    — 4-bit, all four data pins tied to GND, seed = 0, GOLDEN = 0x0. The signature never moves from 0000, so the status pill is permanently green 'match'. The 'good run' end state.\n\n  • MISR_mismatch — 4-bit, same wiring as match, but GOLDEN was deliberately set to 0xF. The live signature is 0x0, the golden is 0xF, status is permanently red 'mismatch'. What a faulty run looks like.\n\n  • MISR_unconfig — 4-bit, fed by four manually-driven INPUTs (d0..d3 in the side panel). No golden value yet, so the pill is amber 'no golden'. Drive the inputs, step the clock, watch SIG evolve, then click ✎ on the GOLDEN field and capture the live value — the pill should flip to green. Toggle one input bit, step again, and red 'mismatch' — that's a fault detection.\n\n  • MISR_wide     — 8-bit version of unconfig, eight inputs wd0..wd7. Wider register = much smaller aliasing probability (1/256 instead of 1/16).\n\n  • MISR_xl       — 32-bit, taps [31, 21, 1, 0] (the standard CRC-32 reciprocal polynomial), 32 manual inputs xd0..xd31. Production-grade scale: aliasing probability ≈ 1 in 4 billion. Demonstrates that the same engine + panel handle wide registers with no extra plumbing — the canvas just gets taller.\n\nAll five MISRs share the same CLOCK — STEP advances every signature together. Switch the DISPLAY pill in SIGNATURE COMPACTORS to HEX or DEC for easier reading of MISR_xl's 32-bit value."
  },
